tions, launch vehicles, ground stations, manufacturing facilities, Terafab, AI compute infrastructure, data centers, and supporting infrastructure.\n\n- **Starship:** "The development, testing, and deployment of Starship in accordance with our anticipated schedule, as well as our pursuit of orbital AI, other space-related services, and lunar and interplanetary missions, will require the investment of significant additional capital resources."\n\n- **AI compute:** "We have made and intend to continue to make substantial capital expenditures to support the growth of our AI products, including costs related to obtaining third-party GPUs, manufacturing our own GPUs, and constructing, leasing, maintaining, enhancing, and expanding our data centers."\n\n- **Acceleration optionality:** "We may choose to increase or accelerate the pace of any of these investments at any time, which could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."\n\n- **AI segment multi-year horizon:** "We expect to allocate substantial capital to expand our compute infrastructure, and we expect a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA. During this investment period, our capital expenditures will scale as quickly as we are able to deploy power and compute to address the **$26.5 trillion potential market opportunity for AI**."\n\n- **Financing plans:** "We plan to access a range of debt and equity financing solutions available to us as a public company to fund future investments in growth and to maintain strong liquidity."\n\n---\n\n## Satellite Manufacturing Capacity\n\nThe documents do not provide a specific numeric satellite manufacturing capacity figure (e.g., units per month). However, they note:\n\n- **Connectivity capex driver:** Capital expenditures are "primarily driven by higher satellite and ground equipment costs as we continue to increase our number of satellites and grow our satellite network."\n- **Satellite launches scaled from 89 in 2024 to 122 in 2025** (Starlink satellite launches), indicating substantial manufacturing throughput.\n- The term **"Terafab"** is referenced among capital-intensive projects, suggesting a satellite or component manufacturing facility scaling initiative, though no specific capacity details are given.\n\n---\n\n## Starship Development Milestones\n\n### Vehicle Capabilities\n- **Starship V3:** Expected to carry a payload of **100 metric tons**\n- **Future generations (potentially Starship V4):** Could reach **200 metric tons**, potentially as soon as Starship V4\n- Starship is expected to be the **only vehicle with fully reusable first and second stages**\n- Expected to **reduce cost to reach orbit by 99% or more** relative to NASA\'s historical average of $18,500 per kilogram\n\n### R&D Investment\n| Period | Space Segment R&D | Note |\n|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $930M | Accelerated investment in Starship vehicle and related facilities |\n| FY 2025 | $3,004M | Accelerated timeline for Starship development (up from $1,835M in FY 2024) |\n| FY 2024 | $1,835M | — |\n| FY 2023 | $1,538M | — |\n\n### Development Status & Outlook\n- R&D costs relate to "development, build, and testing of Starship," including test flight hardware, Raptor engines, employee compensation, tooling, equipment, depreciation for R&D equipment, and allocated overhead.\n- The company expects Space R&D to **increase both in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue in 2026** as it invests in development and commercialization of Starship.\n- R&D is expected to **moderate once Starship is commercialized** by delivering payload to orbit, at which point "Starship costs generally will be capitalized and then depreciated in cost of revenue."\n- Starship is described as "the key enabler of our long-term growth strategy by unlocking entirely new categories of missions" and is "central to our goal of unlocking growth through our unique vertically integrated business model."\n- **Orbital AI compute** is cited as a future infrastructure application enabled by Starship\'s cost reduction.\n\n### 2025 Acceleration Decision\nIn 2025, the company "accelerated [its] timeline for Starship development, increasing R&D in [the] Space segment to $3,004 million, compared to $1,835 million in 2024," reflecting a deliberate decision to prioritize speed as a competitive advantage.',
