    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Connectivity Segment: Revenue Recognition, Subscriber Contracts, ARPU Trends & Seasonality\n\n## Revenue Recognition Policies\n\n### Broadband Services\n- Revenue is recognized **over time** as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefits provided.\n- Revenue is generated from **(i) fixed-price services** requiring advance or recurring monthly payments, or **(ii) variable-priced services** based on actual data consumption.\n- **Broadband contracts** are generally **month-to-month**, and revenue recognized for recurring consumer customers equals the amount billed in that month.\n- Amounts received for advanced payments are included in **deferred revenue** and recognized either **ratably over the subscription term** or based on actual data consumption.\n\n### Starlink Mobile Services\n- Agreements are generally **multi-year contractual obligations ranging from one to five years**, although the customer can generally **terminate at any time**.\n- Starlink Mobile services have **one performance obligation**.\n- Revenue recognition follows the same pattern as broadband (ratably or based on actual data consumption).\n\n### Starshield\n- Revenue is recognized **over time** for certain multi-year contracts using the **cost-to-cost input method**.\n- Revenue is recorded based on costs (materials and labor hours) incurred to date relative to the total estimated cost at completion.\n- Requires significant management judgment for estimating total cost at completion, including assumptions on labor hours, allocation of shared costs for satellite production, satellite material costs, and expected technological changes.\n\n### Starlink Kits (Products)\n- Revenue is recognized **at a point in time** upon **delivery to the customer**, or for certain enterprise customers, **when installed**.\n- Revenue is reported **net of sales returns, credits, and allowances**.\n- **All products revenue** is attributable to the Connectivity segment.\n\n### Multiple Performance Obligations\n- **Substantially all** Starlink customer contracts contain **multiple performance obligations**, typically including **(i) broadband services** and **(ii) the sale of the Starlink Kit** (inclusive of the terminal).\n- For contracts with multiple performance obligations, the Company accounts for individual obligations if they are **distinct**.\n- The **transaction price is allocated** to each performance obligation based on its **standalone selling price**, determined by the price at which the good or service is sold separately to similar customers in similar locations.\n\n### Deferred Revenue\n- Deferred revenue **primarily relates to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise and government contracts**.\n- Total deferred revenue as of **December 31, 2024**: **$10,179 million**, of which **$4,080 million** was recognized as revenue in 2025.\n- Total deferred revenue as of **December 31, 2025**: **$12,116 million**.\n\n---\n\n## Subscriber Contract Terms\n\n| Customer Type | Contract Term | Termination |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Consumer Broadband** | Month-to-month | Generally cancellable |\n| **Starlink Mobile** | 1–5 years (multi-year) | Customer can generally terminate at any time |\n| **Enterprise & Government** | Varies; includes multi-year arrangements | Varies |\n\n---\n\n## ARPU Trends\n\n### Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 (Connectivity Segment)\n- **Starlink Subscribers grew 104.7%**\n- **Starlink Subscriber ARPU declined 22.9%**, primarily due to **international expansion and the addition of lower-priced service plans**\n\n### Full Year 2025 vs. 2024 (Connectivity Segment)\n- **Starlink Subscribers grew 99.9%**\n- **Starlink Subscriber ARPU declined 11.2%**, primarily due to **international expansion and the addition of lower-priced service plans**\n\n### Full Year 2024 vs. 2023 (Connectivity Segment)\n- **Starlink Subscribers grew 96.5%**\n- **Starlink Subscriber ARPU declined 8.1%**, primarily due to **international expansion**\n\n**ARPU Summary Table:**\n\n| Period | Subscriber Growth | ARPU Decline | Primary Drivers |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 vs Q1 2025 | +104.7% | −22.9% | International expansion, lower-priced plans |\n| FY 2025 vs FY 2024 | +99.9% | −11.2% | International expansion, lower-priced plans |\n| FY 2024 vs FY 2023 | +96.5% | −8.1% | International expansion |\n\n---\n\n## Revenue Growth (Connectivity Segment)\n\n| Period | Revenue | YoY Change | YoY % |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $3,257M | +$782M | +31.6% |\n| FY 2025 | $11,387M | +$3,788M | +49.8% |\n| FY 2024 | $7,599M | +$3,730M | +96.4% |\n| FY 2023 | $3,869M | — | — |\n\n**Revenue Composition (FY 2025):**\n- **Consumer**: $7,208M\n- **Enterprise & Government**: $4,179M (includes Starlink Mobile)\n\n---\n\n## Revenue Disaggregation (Products vs. Services)\n\n| | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Products** | $380M | $352M |\n| **Services** | $4,314M | $3,715M |\n| **Total** | $4,694M | $4,067M |\n\nAll products revenue is attributable to the Connectivity segment.\n\n---\n\n## Seasonality & Predictability Disclosures\n\n- **The Company does not explicitly disclose revenue seasonality for the Connectivity segment** in the provided excerpts.\n- However, **seasonality is disclosed for the AI/Advertising segment**, where "overall advertising spend tends to be highest in the fourth quarter of each year... and lowest in the first quarter."\n- **No similar seasonal disclosure is provided for Connectivity**, suggesting the segment\'s subscription-based, month-to-month consumer broadband model and recurring enterprise contracts may exhibit relatively **stable, predictable revenue patterns** rather than pronounced seasonality.\n- The deferred revenue balance growing from $10.2B to $12.1B year-over-year, combined with the predominance of recurring monthly/annual subscriptions, suggests **relatively high revenue predictability** for the segment.\n\n---\n\n## Cost of Revenue Components (Connectivity)\n\nThe Connectivity segment\'s cost of revenue includes:\n- **Depreciation** (inclusive of launch, satellite, and ground infrastructure costs)\n- **Starlink Kit costs**\n- **Shipping and handling costs**\n- **Ground operating expenses**\n- **Employee compensation costs** (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation) for engineering and operations teams\n- **Payment processor fees**\n- **Warranty expense**\n- **Inventory excess and obsolescence**\n- **Customs and duties**',
